's most famous literary ruin.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Whare_Ghaists_And_Houlets_Nightly_Cry_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1213346.jpg/500px-Whare_Ghaists_And_Houlets_Nightly_Cry_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1213346.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/alloway-auld-kirk-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/alloway-auld-kirk-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/alloway-auld-kirk-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/alloway-auld-kirk-5.jpg"],"tags":["ruins-romantic","atmospheric","free-entry","haunted"]},{"name":"Turnberry Castle","county":"Ayrshire","type":"castle","condition":"ruin","era":"13th century","rating":3.5,"reviewCount":30,"access":"free","description":"Fragmentary ruins on the Ayrshire coast, birthplace of Robert the Bruce. Little remains of this pivotal site, but the views across to Ailsa Craig and Arran are magnificent.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/turnberry-castle.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/turnberry-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/turnberry-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/turnberry-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/turnberry-castle-5.jpg"],"tags":["ruins-romantic","coastal","free-entry","photogenic"]},{"name":"Dunure Castle","county":"South Ayrshire","type":"castle","condition":"ruin","era":"13th century","rating":3.9,"reviewCount":380,"access":"free","description":"Ruined Kennedy stronghold on the Ayrshire coast, where the Earl of Cassillis roasted the Commendator of Crossraguel Abbey alive to steal church lands. Dark deeds above a pretty harbour.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/dunure-castle.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/dunure-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunure-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunure-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunure-castle-5.jpg"],"tags":["ruins-romantic","coastal","dark-brooding","free-entry","photogenic"]},{"name":"Amisfield Tower","county":"Dumfries and Galloway","type":"castle","condition":"ruin","era":"16th century","rating":3.7,"reviewCount":120,"access":"exterior-only","description":"A fine 16th-century tower house near Dumfries, one of the best-preserved in southwest Scotland. Charrier family ambition rendered in warm sandstone.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Amisfield_Tower%2C_Tinwald%2C_Dumfriesshire_c.1789._PD-old-100.jpg/500px-Amisfield_Tower%2C_Tinwald%2C_Dumfriesshire_c.1789._PD-old-100.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/wiki-amisfield-tower.jpg"],"tags":["well-preserved","medieval","atmospheric"]},{"name":"Whithorn Priory","county":"Dumfries and Galloway","type":"abbey","condition":"ruin","era":"5th century onwards","rating":4.2,"reviewCount":580,"access":"free","description":"Scotland's cradle of Christianity — where St Ninian built his 'Candida Casa' in the 5th century. The earliest known Christian site in Scotland, still resonant with ancient sanctity.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Whithorn_Priory_20080423_nave.jpg/500px-Whithorn_Priory_20080423_nave.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/whithorn-priory-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/whithorn-priory-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/whithorn-priory-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/whithorn-priory-5.jpg"],"tags":["ruins-romantic","medieval","atmospheric","museum","celtic","free-entry"]},{"name":"Cruggleton Castle","county":"Dumfries and Galloway","type":"castle","condition":"ruin","era":"12th century","rating":3.4,"reviewCount":80,"access":"free","description":"Fragmentary remains of a Norman castle on the Galloway coast, with commanding views over Wigtown Bay. Once a stronghold of the Comyns.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/cruggleton-castle.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/cruggleton-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/cruggleton-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/cruggleton-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/cruggleton-castle-5.jpg"],"tags":["ruins-romantic","coastal","free-entry","norman"]},{"name":"Corsewall Lighthouse","county":"Dumfries and Galloway","type":"castle","condition":"restored","era":"19th century","rating":4.1,"reviewCount":480,"access":"paid","description":"A working lighthouse on Scotland's southwestern tip, now a luxury hotel. Robert Stevenson engineering meets boutique hospitality, with views to Ireland and the Isle of Man.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Corsewell_Lighthouse_and_Hotel_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1708569.jpg/500px-Corsewell_Lighthouse_and_Hotel_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1708569.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/corsewall-lighthouse-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/corsewall-lighthouse-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/corsewall-lighthouse-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/corsewall-lighthouse-5.jpg"],"tags":["well-preserved","coastal","remote","atmospheric","victorian"]},{"name":"Drumcoltran Tower","county":"Dumfries and Galloway","type":"castle","condition":"intact","era":"16th century","rating":3.6,"reviewCount":100,"access":"free","description":"A well-preserved 16th-century tower house in rural Dumfriesshire, with thick walls and a vaulted ground floor. Quiet dignity in the farming heartland.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/drumcoltran-tower.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/drumcoltran-tower-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/drumcoltran-tower-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/drumcoltran-tower-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/drumcoltran-tower-5.jpg"],"tags":["well-preserved","medieval","free-entry"]},{"name":"Kilwinning Abbey","county":"North Ayrshire","type":"abbey","condition":"ruin","era":"12th century","rating":3.9,"reviewCount":320,"access":"free","description":"Romantic ruins of a medieval abbey in the heart of Kilwinning, Ayrshire. Claimed as the birthplace of Scottish Freemasonry and home to a famous annual papingo shoot.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/kilwinning-abbey.jpg","gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/kilwinning-abbey-2.jpg","https:/